<HEADLINE>
<P>
FESTIVAL '90; 
</P>
<P>
MUSIC AND DANCE REVIEWS; 
</P>
<P>
OPEN FESTIVAL; 
</P>
<P>
MACHOVER'S MAGIC IN CYBERARTS FINALE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN HENKEN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tod Machover is one of the reigning masters of computer-aided music making, an 
institutional blueblood from the MIT Media Laboratory via IRCAM in Paris and 
Juilliard. Sunday afternoon he closed out the CyberArts International 
conference at the Biltmore Hotel with a sonically voluptuous, technologically 
dazzling program of his recent works. 
</P>
<P>
The two ensemble pieces involved what Machover calls "hyperinstruments" -- 
amplified, computer-enhanced extensions of normal instruments, with effects 
somewhat like Morton Subotnick's familiar "ghost" electronics. 
</P>
<P>
"Bug-Mudra" is a fast ride in a fun machine, based on two guitars and a modest 
percussion battery. Basically a very sophisticated, techno-pop moto perpetuo, 
it storms along with irresistible energy and elan. 
</P>
<P>
Machover himself conducted, looking something like Woody Allen as a crazed 
musician, wearing a dataglove -- tied into the hyperinstrument system, of 
course -- on his left hand, with its cable sneaking out under his coat like a 
tail. David Starobin and Oren Fader were the virtuosic, tireless guitarists, 
and Amy Knowles plied the percussion. 
</P>
<P>
The most technically simple -- everything is relative -- and shortest piece, 
the taped "Flora," proved the most musically beguiling, with its moody 
transformations of soprano Karol Bennett's voice. Accompanying it was a 
luminous, similarly evolving HDTV video by Yoichiro Kawaguchi. 
</P>
<P>
"Towards the Center" utilized the always effective services of the California 
E.A.R. Unit, conducted by Stephen Mosko, and abetted by the hyperinstrument 
system. Strip away the glossy production, however, and underneath lay a rather 
ordinary neo-romantic essay, conventional in thought and expression.JOHN HENKEN 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Concert Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA091190-0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 274334 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
September 11, 1990, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part F; Page 5; Column 2; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
396 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
FESTIVAL '90; 
</P>
<P>
MUSIC AND DANCE REVIEWS; 
</P>
<P>
OPEN FESTIVAL; 
</P>
<P>
STRANGE SPECIMENS EMERGE FROM 'POOL' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ELIZABETH ZIMMER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Where do choreographers go when they lack places in which they can afford to 
perform? Back to their studios, apparently, where they keep inventing and 
honing dances until an opportunity like Dance Pool comes along. 
</P>
<P>
An Open Festival sharing of resources, Dance Pool enabled local artists and 
visitors from other California centers, to mount three evenings and three 
matinees at the Morgan-Wixson Theatre in Santa Monica. 
</P>
<P>
Joan Nicholson, Michelle Berne and Nancy Fassett shared Friday's opening 
program. In "Grandma," Nicholson, a migrant actress-writer-dancer, spoke 
eloquently of her grandmothers while Stella Matsuda and Sissy Boyd depicted the 
crotchety women she found "hard to love." 
</P>
<P>
A second monologue, "Rented Rooms," set her memoirs of a life lived in 
temporary quarters against a recorded score of overwhelming John Coltrane jazz; 
one struggled to hear the witty commentary. Poised with her notebook at a cafe 
table, she talked while Boyd filled the stage with decorative movement. 
</P>
<P>
Combining dance with text is always tricky; Nicholson succeeded because she is 
a real poet, able to construct economical language that travels well from the 
stage. 
</P>
<P>
Fassett, using the same device of a single personality represented by two 
performers, fell into the trap of psychologizing and described what she was 
already showing, snapshots of a woman driven by the expectations of others. 
Perhaps useful therapeutically, this process flops onstage. 
</P>
<P>
Berne's wordless duets were dramatic; in the first, a man and woman struggled 
on a table while Jane Ira Bloom blew her soprano sax into the body of a grand 
piano. In the second, a woman-in-white midwifed the emergence of a sea spirit 
from a bundle of rags. Berne has studied Butoh; sustained dramatic imagery is 
her strength. 
</P>
<P>
Saturday evening's program included familiar works by Heidi Duckler, Donna 
Sternberg and Jill Jacobson-Bennett, as well as a few premieres, all short. 
</P>
<P>
Sternberg performed "Who are Your Heroes," a promising solo sandbagged by its 
moralizing text but cheered along by Jaston Nishizaki live on harmonica. 
Jacobson-Bennett, a good dancer, offered diverting phrases of movement to such 
trendy accompaniment as the Gipsy Kings and Paul Simon. 
</P>
<P>
A promised premiere from Duckler did not materialize; in its place was "Your 
Knees Are Friends," a 1985 spoof of debutantes by Mary Reid. ELIZABETH ZIMMER 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Dance Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
