<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chip Industry Barometer Falls: The semiconductor industry's benchmark indicator 
dipped in August to its lowest level since November. 
</P>
<P>
The San Jose-based Semiconductor Industry Assn. said the book-to-bill ratio, 
which compares orders with shipments, fell to 0.99 in August from 1 in July. A 
book-to-bill ratio of 0.99 means that for every $100 of semiconductors shipped 
to the U.S. market in the three months ended in August, chip manufacturers 
received new orders worth $99. A ratio of less than 1 is considered unhealthy 
for the industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
ELECTRONICS INDUSTRY -- UNITED STATES; FACTORY ORDERS; SEMICONDUCTORS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA091190-0113 </DOCNO>
