<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: TUSTIN; 
</P>
<P>
NORTH TUSTIN GROUP SEEKS INCORPORATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A group calling itself Citizens for More Local Control will announce plans 
today to promote the incorporation of North Tustin. 
</P>
<P>
Bruce Nestande, a former Orange County supervisor and state assemblyman, and a 
six-year resident of North Tustin, will act as chairman of the group. 
</P>
<P>
Marvin Rawitch, the group's initial organizer, said the plan is to put 
incorporation on the ballot by June, 1991. 
</P>
<P>
"We are divided into two spheres of influence and are being nibbled away by 
piecemeal annexations," Rawitch said. "And staying as a county island no longer 
seems to be a viable option. As a county island, the kind of local control that 
we would like to have is very limited." 
</P>
<P>
Rawitch said the group is in the process of selecting officers and directors 
and will be seeking grass-roots support. 
</P>
<P>
A study funded by Foothill Communities Assn. and unveiled in June at a town 
hall meeting indicated that a utility-users tax would be needed for the 
28,000-resident community to succeed as a city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
